{
  "doc_id": "46248",
  "text": "obesity; Type 2 diabetes; C1q family; energy metabolism; fatty acid oxidation; AMPK ADIPOSE TISSUE SECRETES LARGE numbers of polypeptide hormones and cytokines (collectively termed adipokines) that have local and/or systemic effects on carbohydrate and fat metabolism [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . These secreted metabolic regulators modulate whole body insulin sensitivity and energy metabolism by acting directly on metabolic tissues (e.g., skeletal muscle and liver) or indirectly through regulatory roles in inflammatory processes [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . The list of adipokines has grown considerably over the past 10 years, with leptin and adiponectin being the most widely studied and best understood [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] .",
